pay per job posting or successful hire. Consider offering different pricing tiers based on features and the level of support provided.\n8. Candidate support: Offer resources and tools for job seekers, such as AI-driven resume reviews, personalized job recommendations, and interview preparation resources, to help them improve their chances of success.\n9. Partnerships: Establish partnerships with industry organizations, educational institutions, and other relevant stakeholders to expand your reach and enhance the value of your platform for users.\n10. Legal and compliance: Ensure your platform adheres to data privacy regulations, employment laws, and other relevant compliance requirements in the regions where it operates.\n\nBy focusing on technology-driven solutions and continuous improvement, this AI-powered recruitment platform can potentially disrupt the traditional recruiting agency model, providing a more efficient and cost-effective solution for both employers and job seekers.\nUser: Agency recruiters seem better at traditional tech platforms at driving candidate engagement. In other words they're better at activating passive candidates and they can keep them interested through the interview process. \n\nHow can AI be used to drive engagement in this way?\nAssistant: AI can be used to drive candidate engagement in several ways, helping to activate passive candidates and maintain their interest throughout the interview process. Here are some strategies that can be employed:\n\n1. Personalization: AI can analyze a candidate's profile, preferences, and past interactions to deliver personalized job recommendations, notifications, and content that align with their interests and career goals. This targeted approach can help capture the attention of passive candidates and keep them engaged.\n2. Smart communication: AI-driven chatbots or virtual assistants can interact with candidates, answering their questions, providing information about job opportunities, and guiding them through the application process. These tools can offer a more interactive and engaging experience compared to traditional platforms.\n3. Sentiment analysis: By using natural language processing (NLP) to analyze candidate interactions and feedback, AI can identify patterns in candidate sentiment, helping employers to adjust their communication strategies and address potential concerns to keep candidates engaged.\n4. Gamification: AI can be used to introduce gamification elements, such as skills-based challenges, quizzes, or competitions, to the recruitment process. This can make the experience more enjoyable and engaging, encouraging candidates to stay involved.\n5. Dynamic content: AI can generate dynamic content, such as articles, videos, or learning resources, tailored to each candidate's interests and career goals. By providing relevant and valuable content, you can keep candidates engaged and invested in the process.\n6. Continuous feedback: AI-powered platforms can gather and analyze feedback from candidates throughout the recruitment process. This data can be used to continuously improve the candidate experience, ensuring that the platform remains engaging and effective over time.\n7. Timely follow-ups: AI can automatically schedule and send timely follow-up messages or reminders to candidates, keeping them informed about their application status and ensuring that they remain engaged in the process.\n8. Virtual onboarding: AI-driven tools can be used to create interactive and immersive onboarding experiences, helping candidates feel more connected to their potential employer and engaged throughout the hiring process.\n\nBy leveraging AI to create personalized, interactive, and data-driven experiences, recruitment platforms can better engage passive candidates and maintain their interest throughout the interview process, ultimately leading to more successful hires.\nUser: what's the difference between user research and design research?\nAssistant:", par