INFO 06-17 10:20:31 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-e0ed7ff8dade48e1b7a7bcf8148e7cee-0: prompt: "User: Explain the fault-tolerance of the reaction control system on the Space Shuttle\nAssistant: The reaction control system (RCS) on the Space Shuttle was designed to be fault-tolerant, meaning it was able to continue functioning even if one or more of its components failed. The RCS consisted of two sets of thrusters: primary and secondary. The primary thrusters were located on the aft of the orbiter and were used for major maneuvers such as orbit insertion and deorbit. The secondary thrusters were located on the nose and tail of the orbiter and were used for fine-tuning the spacecraft's attitude, or orientation in space.\n\nEach set of thrusters had multiple redundant thrusters, so that if one failed, the others could still function. Additionally, the RCS was connected to the orbiter's main computer, which monitored the system's performance and could automatically switch to a backup thruster if needed. This ensured that the spacecraft could still be controlled even if a thruster failed.\n\nAll these features made the RCS fault-tolerant and able to continue functioning even in the event of a failure, which made it an important safety feature on the Space Shuttle.\nUser: did the RCS have any on-orbit failures?\nAssistant: There were several instances where the reaction control system (RCS) on the Space Shuttle experienced failures or malfunctions during on-orbit missions. These failures were usually caused by leaks in the thruster system or problems with the RCS valves.\n\nFor example, during the STS-41D mission in 1984, one of the primary RCS thrusters experienced a leak, causing the mission to be shortened. In the STS-51F mission of 1985, a malfunction in one of the RCS valves caused a loss of attitude control, but the crew was able to recover the situation by switching to the backup system.\n\nOn the STS-93 mission in 1999, one of the primary RCS thrusters failed, causing the mission to be shortened and the landing site to be changed. And on the final mission of the Space Shuttle program, STS-135, one of the RCS thrusters experienced a leak, but the mission was able to continue safely.\n\nDespite these failures, the RCS on the Space Shuttle generally performed well and the spacecraft was able to continue its mission safely with the help of the redundant systems.\nUser: Provide more detail on the STS-93 RCS Failure\nAssistant: During the STS-93 mission in 1999, one of the primary reaction control system (RCS) thrusters failed. This caused a loss of control in the yaw axis, meaning the spacecraft was unable to maintain its proper orientation in space. The failure occurred on the second day of the mission and was caused by a leak in one of the RCS fuel lines.\n\nThe crew attempted to use the backup RCS thrusters to maintain control, but they were not powerful enough to compensate for the loss of the primary thruster. As a result, the mission was shortened and the landing site was changed from Kennedy Space Center to Edwards Air Force Base in California.\n\nThe failure was significant because it marked the first time that a primary RCS thruster had failed on an operational Space Shuttle mission. Despite this, the crew was able to safely complete the mission and return to Earth. The RCS had several redundant systems that helped to minimize the impact of the failure, and the crew had been trained to handle this kind of situation.\n\nThe failure prompted NASA to implement a number of changes to the RCS system to prevent similar failures from happening in the future, including the modification of the fuel lines to minimize the risk of leaks, and the better monitoring of the RCS performance.\nUser: Provide a list of RCS failures on the Space Shuttle\nAssistant:", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_t