ompose and the MVVM model.\n\nOne option would be to create a custom composable using a DropDownMenu and BaseTextField, as suggested in one of the Stack Overflow responses [[3](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/64419367/does-jetpack-compose-offer-a-material-autocomplete-textview-replacement)]. This approach would involve creating a ViewModel to hold the list of suggested places based on the user\'s input, and then passing that list to the custom composable to display in the DropDownMenu.\n\nAnother option would be to use a hybrid approach that combines XML-autocomplete and Compose screens through the ComposeView, as suggested in another Stack Overflow response [[3](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/64419367/does-jetpack-compose-offer-a-material-autocomplete-textview-replacement)]. This approach would involve creating an XML layout with a Material AutoCompleteTextView, and then using the ComposeView to inflate that layout and wrap it in a Compose Column to display the selected place in a LazyColumn.\n\nFinally, there is a tutorial available on the Google Codelabs website that walks through building adaptive apps with Jetpack Compose, including how to use Compose to enhance reachability and build responsive UIs on different device types [[1](https://codelabs.developers.google.com/jetpack-compose-adaptability)]. While this tutorial doesn\'t specifically cover Google Places autocomplete, it may still be a useful resource for learning more about building Compose apps in general.\n\nI hope this information is helpful! Let me know if you have any further questions.\nUser: Hey, I want you to build to google places autocomplete on jetpack compose using the MVVM model\n\nSo the user will type the place in a textfield and the list of places with postalCode will display in a lazyColumn with the user able to select from the lazyColumn a place\nAssistant:', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=