ok into other workflow-related projects and technologies offered by the Spring ecosystem, such as Spring Web Flow or Activiti. These are both popular, well-documented, and widely-used frameworks for building workflow-based applications with the Spring framework.\nUser: can i use spring state machine and temporal workflow together and is it justified?\nAssistant: Yes, you can use Spring State Machine and Temporal Workflow together. Whether it\'s justified to use both in a single project depends on the requirements and complexity of your use case.\n\nSpring State Machine is a framework for modeling and executing state machines, while Temporal Workflow is a cloud-native workflow engine that provides a way to model and execute workflows. If your application requires a combination of state machine and workflow behavior, using both in combination can be a good solution. However, if your requirements can be met by either one of these frameworks alone, it may be more appropriate to choose only one of them.\n\nIt\'s worth noting that Temporal Workflow provides a workflow engine, while Spring State Machine provides a state machine framework. The two can be used together, but it may take some effort to integrate them and ensure that they work together effectively. Ultimately, the decision to use both will depend on the specific requirements of your use case.\nUser: give me an example as to how will we use in an complex lending mortgage application with customer, front office banker and back office tasks\nAssistant: Here\'s a high-level example of how you might use Spring State Machine and Temporal Workflow in a complex lending mortgage application with customer, front office banker, and back office tasks:\n\n1. Spring State Machine could be used to model and manage the state of the mortgage application process. For example, you could define states for "Submitted", "Under Review", "Approved", "Rejected", etc. Transitions between these states could be triggered by events such as