INFO 06-17 10:21:23 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-d5fce13579fc4be5bc72781bb1c7ba2b-0: prompt: "User: please help me plan a 5-day Kyoto trip.\n\nNote: \n\nThe itinerary should include restaurants, tourist attractions, accommodations, and means of transportation.\nThe budget shouldn’t exceed 20000 yen per day.\nThe itinerary should make sense, e.g., restaurant should near the tourist attractions, you shouldn’t go outside of Kyoto like staying at a hotel in Tokyo.\nAssistant: Sure, I'd be happy to help you plan your 5-day trip to Kyoto! Here's a sample itinerary that should fit your budget of 20,000 yen per day:\n\nDay 1:\n\n* Morning: Visit Fushimi Inari Shrine, famous for its thousands of vermilion torii gates that form a tunnel up the mountain. This shrine is easily accessible by train and is free to visit.\n* Lunch: Have lunch at Inari Sushi Koji, located near the shrine. This restaurant serves traditional sushi, including inari-zushi, a type of sushi wrapped in sweetened tofu pouches.\n* Afternoon: Visit Kiyomizu-dera Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the most famous temples in Kyoto. The temple offers a stunning view of the city from its wooden stage. Admission fee is 400 yen.\n* Dinner: Try some Kyoto-style shojin ryori (vegetarian Buddhist cuisine) at Shigetsu, located within the temple grounds. This restaurant offers a set menu for around 4,000 yen per person.\n\nDay 2:\n\n* Morning: Take a stroll through Arashiyama Bamboo Grove, located in western Kyoto. This is a serene and picturesque bamboo forest that is free to visit.\n* Lunch: Try some traditional soba noodles at Okutan, a restaurant near the bamboo grove. Soba is a type of thin noodle made from buckwheat flour.\n* Afternoon: Visit Tenryu-ji Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the most important temples in Kyoto. The temple features a beautiful garden that changes with the seasons. Admission fee is 500 yen.\n* Dinner: Have some kaiseki ryori (multi-course haute cuisine) at Gion Karyo, located in the historic Gion district. This restaurant offers a set menu for around 10,000 yen per person.\n\nDay 3:\n\n* Morning: Visit Kinkaku-ji Temple, also known as the Golden Pavilion, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the most iconic sights in Kyoto. The temple is covered in gold leaf and reflects beautifully in the surrounding pond. Admission fee is 400 yen.\n* Lunch: Have some udon noodles at Omen, a restaurant located near the temple. Udon is a type of thick noodle made from wheat flour.\n* Afternoon: Visit Nijo Castle, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and former residence of the Tokugawa shoguns. The castle features beautiful gardens and a famous nightingale floor that chirps when walked upon. Admission fee is 1,000 yen.\n* Dinner: Try some yakitori (grilled chicken skewers) at Torito, located in the Pontocho district. This restaurant offers a variety of chicken parts grilled to perfection.\n\nDay 4:\n\n* Morning: Take a day trip to Nara, a city located about 45 minutes from Kyoto by train. Visit Todai-ji Temple, a UNESCO World Heritage Site and home to the largest bronze Buddha statue in the world. Admission fee is 600 yen.\n* Lunch: Have some kakinoha-zushi (sushi wrapped in persimmon leaves) at Nakatanidou, a famous sushi shop in Nara.\n* Afternoon: Visit Nara Park, a large park that is home to over 1,000 wild deer. You can feed and interact with the deer, and visit other attractions such as Kasuga-taisha Shrine and Nara National Museum.\n* Dinner: Try some yakiniku (Japanese BBQ) at Yakiniku Motoyama, located near Kyoto Station. This restaurant offers a variety of meats and vegetables for grilling.\n\nDay 5:\n\n* Morning: Visit the Kyoto Imperial Palace, the former\nUser: continue\nAssistant:", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=F