loyees GROUP BY department;\n6. HAVING\n* The HAVING keyword is used to filter the groups generated by a GROUP BY statement.\n* It specifies the conditions that must be met for a group to be included in the result set.\n* Examples of HAVING statements:\n\t+ SELECT department, AVG(salary) FROM employees GROUP BY department HAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;\n\t+ SELECT department, COUNT(*) FROM employees GROUP BY department HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;\n7. JOIN\n* The JOIN keyword is used to combine rows from two or more tables based on a related column between them.\n* It is often used to retrieve data that is spread across multiple tables in a database.\n* Examples of JOIN statements:\n\t+ SELECT \\* FROM employees JOIN departments ON employees.department\\_id = departments.department\\_id;\n\t+ SELECT employees.first\\_name, employees.last\\_name, departments.department\\_name FROM employees JOIN departments ON employees.department\\_id = departments.department\\_id;\n\nI hope this helps you fill up your Word document with the necessary details for each basic instruction in SQL! Let me know if you need any further assistance.\nUser: Rédige seuelement cette fiche pour les isntructions SELECT, FROM et WHERE de manière très détaillée avec une partie dédiée à des exmples concrets\n\nPlease write in English language.\nAssistant:", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=8, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [71703, 25, 52366, 0, 5692, 525, 279, 3565, 369, 1817, 6770, 7600, 304, 7870, 429, 646, 5155, 705, 825, 2150, 1817, 304, 264, 9322, 2197, 1447, 16, 13, 19094, 198, 9, 576, 19094, 5114, 374, 1483, 311, 17179, 821, 504,