INFO 06-17 10:21:33 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-7034bfa09abb41f29696550d16cc428e-0: prompt: "Assistant: INSERT INTO:\nThe INSERT INTO statement is used to insert new data into an existing table. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, column3,...)\nVALUES (value1, value2, value3,...);\n```\nThis statement inserts a new row into the table with the specified values for each column. The column names and values must match in order.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nINSERT INTO employees (first_name, last_name, age, salary)\nVALUES ('John', 'Doe', 35, 50000);\n```\nUPDATE:\nThe UPDATE statement is used to modify existing data in a table. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nUPDATE table_name\nSET column1 = value1, column2 = value2, ...\nWHERE some_column = some_value;\n```\nThis statement updates the specified columns in the table with the new values, for the rows that meet the specified condition.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nUPDATE employees\nSET salary = 60000\nWHERE last_name = 'Doe';\n```\nDELETE:\nThe DELETE statement is used to delete data from a table. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nDELETE FROM table_name\nWHERE some_column = some_value;\n```\nThis statement deletes the rows that meet the specified condition from the table.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nDELETE FROM employees\nWHERE age > 60;\n```\nCREATE TABLE:\nThe CREATE TABLE statement is used to create a new table in the database. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE table_name (\n    column1 datatype,\n    column2 datatype,\n    column3 datatype,\n    ...\n);\n```\nThis statement creates a new table with the specified columns and data types.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE employees (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY,\n    first_name VARCHAR(50),\n    last_name VARCHAR(50),\n    age INT,\n    salary DECIMAL(10,2)\n);\n```\nALTER TABLE:\nThe ALTER TABLE statement is used to modify the structure of an existing table. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nALTER TABLE table_name\nADD column_name datatype;\n```\nThis statement adds a new column to the existing table.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nALTER TABLE employees\nADD department VARCHAR(50);\n```\nDROP TABLE:\nThe DROP TABLE statement is used to delete an existing table from the database. The basic syntax of the statement is as follows:\n```sql\nDROP TABLE table_name;\n```\nThis statement deletes the specified table and all its data from the database.\n\nExample:\n```sql\nDROP TABLE employees;\n```\nUser: Keep this formatting with the previous instructions : \nJOIN:\nThe JOIN instruction is used to combine data from two or more tables based on a related column between them. There are several types of JOINs in SQL, including INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, RIGHT JOIN, and FULL OUTER JOIN. Here are some important details to keep in mind when using JOIN:\n• The columns used to join the tables must have the same data type and value range.\n• You must specify the type of JOIN you want to use (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL OUTER).\n• You can join more than two tables by using multiple JOIN instructions in a single query.\n\nExample:\nSELECT employees.first\\_name, departments.department\\_name\nFROM employees\nINNER JOIN departments\nON employees.department\\_id = departments.department\\_id;\n\nPlease write in English language.\nAssistant:", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=8, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None), prompt_token_ids: [71703, 25, 39518, 12496, 510, 785, 39518, 12496, 5114, 374, 1483, 311, 5656, 501, 821, 1119, 458, 6350, 1965, 13, 576, 6770, 19482, 315,