leware and guards to protect the routes and ensure that only authorized users can access certain functionality.\n6. Test the API using a tool like Postman to ensure that all the endpoints are working as expected and returning the correct data.\n\nOverall, my approach would be to use NestJS and Prisma ORM to quickly and easily set up a scalable and maintainable backend for this application, while following best practices for authentication and authorization.\nUser: Great, can you give me a Prisma Schema for this?\nAssistant: Sure, here is an example Prisma schema for this application:\n```\ntype Chef {\n  id: ID! @id\n  name: String!\n  meals: [Meal!]! @relation(name: "ChefMeals")\n}\n\ntype Meal {\n  id: ID! @id\n  name: String!\n  ratings: [Rating!]! @relation(name: "MealRatings")\n}\n\ntype Rating {\n  id: ID! @id\n  stars: Int!\n  meal: Meal! @relation(name: "MealRatings")\n  customer: Customer! @relation(name: "CustomerRatings")\n}\n\ntype Customer {\n  id: ID! @id\n  name: String!\n  ratings: [Rating!]! @relation(name: "CustomerRatings")\n}\n```\nThis schema defines the four main types in the application - `Chef`, `Meal`, `Rating`, and `Customer` - along with their relationships to each other. For example, a `Chef` can have many `Meal`s, and a `Meal` can have many `Rating`s from `Customer`s.\n\nUsing this schema, we can easily perform CRUD operations on the different types, as well as query for the relationships between them. For example, we could query for all the meals for a given chef, or all the ratings for a given meal.\nUser: Your syntax is not quite right, it\'s more like this example in their docs:\nmodel User {\n id Int @id @default(autoincrement())\n email String @unique\n name String?\n posts Post[]\n}\n\nmodel Post {\n id Int @id @default(autoincrement())\n title String\n content String?\n published Boolean @default(false)\n author User @relation(fields: [authorId], references: [id])\n authorId Int\n}\n\nCan you fix the code you gave me?\nAssistant: