INFO 06-17 10:21:57 logger.py:37] Received request cmpl-37b7f928a51f4bd3a9066c26d9f65ed0-0: prompt: 'User: explain cohesion coupling in detail with examples\nAssistant: Cohesion and coupling are two important concepts in software engineering that refer to the degree of interdependence between different modules or components of a software system.\n\nCohesion refers to the degree to which the elements within a single module work together to achieve a single, well-defined goal. A module with high cohesion is characterized by having a clear, single purpose and all of its elements work together to achieve that purpose. An example of a module with high cohesion might be a module that performs a specific mathematical calculation, where all of the functions and variables within that module are related to that calculation.\n\nOn the other hand, coupling refers to the degree to which different modules or components of a software system depend on each other. A system with high coupling has many interdependent modules, while a system with low coupling has modules that are independent and can be changed or modified without affecting the rest of the system. An example of a module with low coupling might be a module that displays information to the user, which can be modified or changed without affecting other parts of the system.\n\nIt is generally considered good software design practice to aim for high cohesion and low coupling in a software system. High cohesion helps to make a module easy to understand and maintain, since all of its elements are related to a single purpose. Low coupling helps to make a system more flexible and easier to modify, since changes to one module are less likely to affect other parts of the system.\nUser: types of cohesion with examples\nAssistant: There are several types of cohesion that can be identified in software systems, including:\n\n1. Functional cohesion: This refers to the degree to which all the elements within a module work together to perform a single, well-defined function. An example of functional cohesion might be a module that performs a specific mathematical calculation, where all of the functions and variables within that module are related to that calculation.\n2. Sequential cohesion: This refers to the degree to which the elements within a module are organized in a logical sequence to achieve a specific goal. An example of sequential cohesion might be a module that processes a series of inputs in a specific order to produce an output.\n3. Communicational cohesion: This refers to the degree to which the elements within a module work together to exchange information or data. An example of communicational cohesion might be a module that receives input from one source and sends output to another.\n4. Temporal cohesion: This refers to the degree to which the elements within a module are related to a specific point in time. An example of temporal cohesion might be a module that performs a specific task at a specific time, such as a module that sends an email reminder at a certain time of day.\n5. Procedural cohesion: This refers to the degree to which the elements within a module work together to follow a specific process or procedure. An example of procedural cohesion might be a module that performs a series of steps in a specific order to achieve a goal.\n6. Logical cohesion: This refers to the degree to which the elements within a module are related by a common theme or purpose. An example of logical cohesion might be a module that performs various tasks related to managing a customer database, where all of the functions within the module are related to managing the database.\nUser: types of coupling with examples\nAssistant:', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=-1, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=8, min_t