ompare isso com o salário médio das indústrias que geram energia renovável. Vezes o número de pessoas empregados na industria.\n[3/7, 3:05 PM] Otávio Bopp: Mais especificamente, vc tem que tentar modelar isso por kw/h\n[3/7, 3:06 PM] Otávio Bopp: E esse cálculo inclui empregos adjacentes\n[3/7, 3:07 PM] Otávio Bopp: Por exemplo, as pessoas que trabalham em postos de gasolina iam ser incluidas no cálculo sobre petróleo. \n\nE quem faz instalações ou manutenção de painéis solares entraria pro cálculo da energia renovável\nAssistant: It seems like you and your friend are discussing ways that the author could provide evidence to support their claim about the potential negative impacts of transitioning to green energy. Specifically, you suggest using an economic model to compare the average salaries and number of employees in the oil and gas industry versus the renewable energy industry, while also factoring in adjacent jobs such as gas station attendants and solar panel installers. This could potentially provide insight into the economic impact of a transition to green energy, including any potential job losses or gains.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that such an analysis would only provide one piece of the puzzle when it comes to the overall impact of transitioning to green energy. There are many other factors that would need to be considered, such as the long-term environmental impact of continued reliance on fossil fuels, the potential economic benefits of developing new technologies and industries related to renewable energy, and the social and political implications of transitioning away from traditional energy sources. Ultimately, any argument about the costs and benefits of transitioning to green energy would need to take all of these factors into account in order to provide a comprehensive analysis.\nUser: All of these factors could be modelled into an economic modell based on the Ramnsey-Cass-Koupass model. For instance, the benefits of better air quality could